    <title>Combined summary - A Post Quantum Migration Proposal</title>
    <updated>2025-09-22T14:49:51.825076+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAEM=y+Wr4g+kcZpjSUEVay_NCdZcwGSEHcC6W9PcjpibYwd-sA@mail.gmail.com/T/#m376871ab5341f27343e4e85b66d86ca373a5b857" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2025-09-15 16:24:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The discussion revolves around a comprehensive proposal to address the potential threat posed by quantum computing to Bitcoin's cryptographic security. The proposal outlines a phased approach designed to transition Bitcoin to post-quantum cryptography (PQ), thereby safeguarding it against quantum attacks that could exploit current cryptographic primitives.
Phase A of the proposal involves prohibiting transactions to addresses vulnerable to quantum decryption, thus promoting the adoption of PQ-resistant address types. Phase B escalates this protection by invalidating spends from these quantum-vulnerable outputs, effectively freezing funds at addresses not compliant with post-quantum cryptographic standards. This phase is set to be activated approximately five years after Phase A's implementation, following a well-publicized announcement. Phase C, which is considered optional pending further research and consensus, suggests the possibility of reintroducing access to the frozen UTXOs through a fork that would allow legacy funds to be recovered via a zero-knowledge proof demonstrating ownership of the original seed phrase.
This strategy is motivated by the imperative to secure the value stored in the Bitcoin network and minimize incentives for quantum attacks. It is underscored by the radical advancements in quantum computing, which present unprecedented threats to Bitcoin's current cryptographic foundations. With significant investments flowing into quantum computing research and development, the prospect of cryptographically relevant quantum computers emerging within the next few years is taken seriously. Such developments could potentially enable attackers to derive private keys from public keys exposed on the blockchain, posing a direct threat to approximately 25% of Bitcoin currently in circulation.
The proposal is presented as a defensive measure rather than an offensive attack on quantum computing. It aims to act preemptively to mitigate risks and ensure the security of funds by encouraging migration to quantum-resistant cryptographic schemes. The proposal also emphasizes the importance of a clear and unified timeline for the transition, aligning stakeholders across the ecosystem to minimize disruption and maximize resilience against quantum threats.
Moreover, the proposal reflects on the broader implications of implementing such significant changes to Bitcoinâ€™s protocol. It acknowledges the potential conflicts between preserving Bitcoin's fundamental properties, such as conservatism and the right to property, against the necessity to adapt and upgrade in response to evolving technological landscapes. The discussions highlight the delicate balance between taking decisive action to protect the network and maintaining the decentralized, permissionless ethos that underpins Bitcoin.</summary>
